passages.text: Delayed recovery with longer term considerations on earnings quality; Neutral
RHC.AX 12m Price Target: A\$36.80 Price: A\$34.09 Upside: \(7.9\%\)

Our key observations from RHC's FY25 result include; (1) Limited early traction from the initiatives on the Australian business with 2H25 EBIT margin declining \(\sim 70\) bps vs pcp. FY26 guidance however in our view reflects margin accretion, adjusting for the impact of declining profitability of RHC's public work, (2) Insight into the materiality of RHC's public work with the revised Jondalup public hospital agreement representing a drag of \(\sim 600\) bps to FY26 growth (vs pcp). We view this segment of RHC's earnings as lower quality given RHC's limited pricing power with state governments relative to private insurers, (3) Ramsay Sante outperformed with RHC progressing its evaluation of strategic options relating to its \(52.8\%\) shareholding. Retain Neutral with the delay to margin trajectory in Australia and management of the new Jondalup funding mechanism likely to represent an overhang to the stock.

Australia: The 2H25 EBIT performance \((- 5\% / - 9\%)\) vs GS/VA cons) reinforces our view that the initiatives deployed to accelerate performance is a multi- year journey (discussed in detail here). The increase in utilization (300bps 4Q25 vs pcp) is a step in the right direction. This trajectory however is set to be challenged by a significant decline in profitability from state funded work with the 1H26 result potentially providing better clarity to assess the materiality to earnings from RHC's public case mix. The digital & data scope has been reduced with RHC reducing \(\sim 50\) heads in this team. We maintain our expectation of this initiative representing a recurring spend to deliver RHC's EBIT uplift into FY27 and beyond.

Sante: 2H25 EBIT performance was ahead of expectations \((+69\% / + 46\%)\) vs GS/VA cons) with EBIT margin accretion (vs pcp) achieved despite constrained funding. We attribute this to stronger cost discipline, noting lower capex incurred in FY25 (vs pcp).

RHC is the largest private hospital operator in Australia and has operations in the UK, France and the Nordics. The Australian business is the key earnings driver for the group, representing \(\sim 70\%\) of group EBIT (adjusting for Sante's minority stake). The aging demographic and lagging public hospital capacity investment in our view will support long term organic growth for the private hospital sector. Overcapacity in the private sector however has weighed on operator profitability and as supply normalises, we forecast RHC's earnings margins to improve from volume leverage, supporting our long- term valuation for the business. Given RHC's industry leading profitability we do not forecast a near- term step change in earnings from operational improvements and view consensus earnings expectations as too optimistic, underpinning our Neutral recommendation.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
